<p>Eighty-eight keys on a keyboard, the light from the window touching each one.</p>

<p>I sit and watch it although nothing is happening. A room full of stillness, but if you sit still long enough too you can start to notice the more subtle movements. Like the light on the piano keys.</p>

<hr />

<p>Iâ€™ve never been good at maintaining the objects that make up my life. Iâ€™ve had this pair of glasses for almost eight years now. They are a little crooked and the paint on the edges is chipping.</p>

<p>We all need someone to take care of us when our paint chips.</p>

<hr />

<p>The keyboard keys have scuffs and discoloration. Marks of times when they were played for hours, for days, for months. And marks of times when dust collected because I was too busy for music.</p>

<p>But when we care for music, music takes care of us. A solvent turning our stress to stillness again.</p>

<hr />

<p>Of whom do you care? Of what do you care? Who takes care of you?</p>

<p>There is only one rule of life. To care, to show attention, kindness, and enthusiasm.</p>

<p>Care has no time scale or deadline. It is infinite in its energy and devotion.</p>

